ly suspicions, but he said at a&#10;venture, â€œWendy, I ran away the day I was born.â€&#10;&#10;Wendy was quite surprised, but interested; and she indicated in the&#10;charming drawing-room manner, by a touch on her night-gown, that he&#10;could sit nearer her.&#10;&#10;â€œIt was because I heard father and mother,â€ he explained in a low&#10;voice, â€œtalking about what I was to be when I became a man.â€ He was&#10;extraordinarily agitated now. â€œI donâ€™t want ever to be a man,â€ he said&#10;with passion. â€œI want always to be a little boy and to have fun. So I&#10;ran away to Kensington Gardens and lived a long long time among the&#10;fairies.â€&#10;&#10;She gave him a look of the most intense admiration, and he thought it&#10;was because he had run away, but it was really because he knew fairies.&#10;Wendy had lived such a home life that to know fairies struck her as&#10;quite delightful. She poured out questions about them, to his surprise,&#10;for they were rather a nuisance to him, getting in his way and so on,&#10;and indeed he sometimes had to give them a hiding. Still, he liked them&#10;on the whole, and he told her about the beginning of fairies.&#10;&#10;â€œYou see, Wendy, when the first baby laughed for the first time, its&#10;laugh broke into a thousand pieces, and they all went skipping about,&#10;and that was the beginning of fairies.â€&#10;&#10;Tedious talk this, but being a stay-at-home she liked it.&#10;&#10;â€œAnd so,â€ he went on good-naturedly, â€œthere ought to be one fairy for&#10;every boy and girl.â€&#10;&#10;â€œOught to be? Isnâ€™t there?â€&#10;&#10;â€œNo. You see children know such a lot now, they soon donâ€™t believe in&#10;fairies, and every time a child says, â€˜I donâ€™t believe in fairies,â€™&#10;there is a fairy somewhere that falls down dead.â€&#10;&#10;Really, he thought they had now talked enough about fairies, and it&#10;struck him that Tinker Bell was keeping very quiet. â€œI canâ€™t think&#10;where she has gone to,â€ he said